Main function

  • name of function: cc_rss
  • inputs:
    • marginal associations (z-scores) \(\hat{z}\)
    • correlation matrix \(R\)
    • annotation file
  • outputs:
    • PIPs of all annotations

Generate inputs

The GWAS z-scores are from a VCF file downloaded from UKBiobank GWAS summary statistics. See cTWAS tutorial for detailed download instructions.

z_snp.original <- readRDS("source_data/gwas_summary_stats/expand_ukb-d-30780_irnt.RDS")
# print(z_snp.original)
head(z_snp.original)

Simulation example 1: (random samples from chromosome one)

Subsample summary statistics in one chromosome

Here is an example to subsample z-scores within chromosome 1 for later analysis:

seed <- 123
ld_regions <- "EUR"
ld_regions_version <- "b38"
# generate z_snp from the first chromosome
chrom_n <- 1
blks_num <- 20 # select how many blocks in one chromosome
z_snp_subset <- subset_z_snp(z_snp.original = z_snp.original,
                             chrom_n = chrom_n,
                             blks_num = blks_num,
                             ld_regions = ld_regions,
                             ld_regions_version = ld_regions_version,
                             seed = seed)
head(z_snp_subset)
##        CHROM      POS  POS_END          id A1 A2          z blk
## 94292      1 20397715 20397715    rs653910  C  G  1.1786374  14
## 96748      1 20907442 20907442    rs653017  G  A  0.5476441  14
## 360077     1 81266794 81266794  rs61770049  C  T  0.2839387  50

Run using null weight

Now, run the cc_rss function using the null weight. Note that whether using the null weight only influence the prior for \(\pi\), but not the prior for \(\sigma^2\) (variance).

#              ld_regions_version = ld_regions_version,
#              outputdir = outputdir,
#              outname = outname,
#              max.iter = 10,

#    user   system  elapsed

plot_res <- function(f_name){
  cc.df.hpc.allchr <- read.table(f_name, header = T)
cc.df.hpc.allchr$Annt <- as.factor(cc.df.hpc.allchr$Annt)
g1 <- cc.df.hpc.allchr %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=iter, y=pi, group=Annt, color=Annt)) +
  geom_line()

g2 <- cc.df.hpc.allchr %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=iter, y=sigma2, group=Annt, color=Annt)) +
  geom_line()

return(list(g1, g2))
}
## Test with all snps with 10 iterations using function cc_rss
cc.res <-plot_res("/dartfs/rc/lab/S/Szhao/qiaoxue/caucon/results/test_cc_nw/results_test_cc_debug_rds_complete_v1_cc_rss.txt")

Run cc_rss on hpc

Run R file /dartfs/rc/lab/S/Szhao/qiaoxue/caucon/caucon_test_hpc_nonparallel.R. May want to change the first line (content in .libPaths) to your own library directory. May want to change the outputdir and outname before running the code. The Annotation file and GWAS summary scores were generated in the Simulation 2 section in this tutorial and can be modified using the code above.

Submit the batch file (/dartfs/rc/lab/S/Szhao/qiaoxue/caucon/cc_hpc_ver_R_nonparallel.sh) to hpc to run R code (caucon_test_hpc_nonparallel.R) on hpc. The hpc output file (i.e.error and output files) is stored in /dartfs/rc/lab/S/Szhao/qiaoxue/caucon/hpc_output/; the output from the R code (if run successfully) is in the same output directory specified in caucon_test_hpc_nonparallel.R.

Data visualization for cc_rss output in caucon_test_hpc_nonparallel.R is presented here:

## Test with all snps with 30 iterations using function cc_rss_parallel after accelerations

Q & TO DO:

  • The GWAS summary data rely on b37, but the R matrix and regionfile used rely on b38. Therefore, there will be. mismatch in the postion of the SNPs, but using ID to select is safe.
    • Next step: find some other GWAS summary data that rely on b38 or some other R matrix rely on b37
  • More simulations & testing
  • Make it faster. Current bottleneck: readRDS in cc_rss R_snp.ori (Parallelization on multiple cores may not be able to accelerate the file reading process. Multi-task parallelization might work.)
